    "id": "news-1783764595270-2",
    "title": "Mobile Money Fills Financial Void Amid Somalia’s Post-1991 Instability",
    "original_title": "When Cash Failed, Connection Became Currency",
    "slug": "mobile-money-fills-financial-void-amid-somalia-s-post-1991-instability",
    "summary": "After the 1991 collapse of Somalia’s central government, mobile money systems emerged as a trusted alternative to cash, reshaping how Somalis save, transfer, and access funds without formal banking.",
    "content": "The collapse of Somalia’s central government in 1991 left the country without functioning public institutions, damaged infrastructure, and a shattered banking system. With formal financial services in ruins, confidence in the Somali shilling plummeted, and many transactions shifted to the U.S. dollar. In this environment, cash became cumbersome—physically fragile, difficult to transport, and increasingly mistrusted.\n\nOut of this void, mobile money platforms like Hormuud’s EVC Plus and, later, Telesom’s Zaad, took root. These services allowed users to send and receive funds using basic mobile phones, without needing a bank account. By leveraging existing telecommunications networks and agent-based cash-in/cash-out points, they provided a simple, accessible solution for daily commerce and remittances.\n\nThe success of mobile money in Somalia was not driven by government policy but by grassroots adaptation. Entrepreneurs and local telecoms recognized the need for a reliable value transfer system when traditional currency failed. This innovation enabled households to manage expenses, businesses to trade, and diaspora families to send money home more efficiently.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, mobile money has been transformative. It offers a secure channel to remit funds to relatives, bypassing costly and slow formal banking channels. The system also fosters trust—users can verify transactions instantly, and agents are often familiar community members. This has strengthened economic ties between Somalis abroad and those at home.\n\nToday, mobile money is deeply embedded in Somali daily life. It supports everything from paying salaries to buying groceries. While challenges like regulation, interoperability, and fraud remain, the system stands as a testament to local innovation in the face of institutional collapse. For the diaspora, it remains a vital link—a currency rebuilt on connection.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/11/when-cash-failed-connection-became-currency/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=when-cash-failed-connection-became-currency",
